I really like this game. It's a decent puzzle adventure. A bit on the short side given the price, but you can tell that you're paying for a genuine and painstakingly handcrafted game with well balanced story and hand drawn artwork in every animation of every scene. So, what it lacks for in length of game, it makes up for in immersion. If you like adventure games, do yourself a favor and buy this! A piece of warning though, if you're contemplating buying this game because some "games like this game" website recommended it for similarities to The Room series... Don't buy it for that reason. It's just as satisfying, but is not the same aside from being a puzzler.. I add that last part because I first contemplated purchasing Machinarium for that very reason. I realize now that, had I bought it for that reason I'd be thoroughly disappointed and wouldn't have been able to enjoy it as much as it deserves to be deserved.

story, puzzles, and most of all hand drawn fantastical art all wrapped up

input devices. I highly recommend anything Amanita Design creates because 
you will be blown away by their masterpieces.

Game has beautiful design, however there are two glaring mistakes that make it ridiculously difficult. One is that there is no indication of what you can interact with. The thing you need to interact with looks no different than the backgrounds, which is just ridiculous.  Secondly, once you have an object that you can use in some way with something else in your field of view, the robot shakes his head like an idiot unless you are literally right on top of whatever it is that the object will work with. I can't tell you how frustrating it is to waste your time going from room to room when you've decided something won't work, only to discover that if the robot had been mere pixels closer he would've interacted. content: The environments are impressive and the main character and story is very relatable, but the actual puzzles are repetitive, too easy, yet hard because of ambiguouity about where the next step is so you'll likely have to cheat a lot. Some puzzles require you to tap the same object twice or many times in a row, and some objects don't stand out at all from the background. In the PC version apparently you get a cursor effect, but here you get nothing.  Some other annoyances: It's too easy to lose your progress if you have fat fingers and press "new game" instead of "continue" (you can still save and load safely however). You also can't turn the music off.

One of the best point & click adventure games I've seen for Android. I saw lots of complaints about the puzzles being too hard and I beat this in around 24-hours of game time, using the walkthrough "cheat" only 2-3 times (the music puzzle was the only one I couldn't figure out on my own because I'm tone-deaf). All I can say is that I am glad that they included the walk through with the game as a tool to be used if necessary. If you knew the answers to all of the puzzles this game would take about 1-2 hours to fully play through, but if you don't know the puzzles and you don't know where to go and what to do next this game takes at least 6 plus hours to complete. All in all, definitely worth the $5 I was charged. I would buy the sequel.

If you like games where you need to randomly click on every object in the screen, go for it. But there's no rhyme or reason for which objects are manipulable and which are just background art-work (actually take what I said 3x - the robot has 3 height settings and your ability to interact with objects changes based on how tall you are when you tap).  It's not hard, it's dumb. It's not free form, so you can't explore per say or really figure things out. You need to somehow do them in the order the game prescribed by, like I said above, randomly clicking on everything.  Pros: Art-work is beautiful. I like that there's a built-in tutorial (because, again, you can't figure this out on your own - not because it's a challenge but because there's no rhyme or reason to what works and what doesn't), and I like that you have to solve a "puzzle" to get to the tutorial.

First off this game has top notch art and music score that makes it interesting and great to look at and listen to. I guess my complaint is that every puzzle has to be solved in a strict linear sequence and in one certain order with most puzzles requiring you to figure out the correct sequence of clicks/taps as well as solve the puzzle.  Basically its more of a collection of demanding puzzles strung together with a thin story than it is an adventure with well paced game play. Realizing that this is a really challenging set of puzzles and not expecting a story driven casual adventure (its listed as adventure in the Play Store) you'll be happy with this app.

Your enjoyment of this game will be directly proportional to whether you like the old tropes of PC point-and-click adventure games. It has plenty of rough edges when playing this type of game on a touch screen device, but the developers seem to have done all they can to make it work best. You'll feel great when you figure something out, infuriated when you can't make something work, and dopey when you go to the hints and have it spelled out for you. Kudos for Play Games support, hope they add more to it.

There are few good point and click old style adventure games on Google Play. So far this has been top one along with the remastered Broken Sword series on android. Beautiful Story. If you are not fond of reading in the game and hate so much instructions it also makes up for it.  I understand there's also a version on PC. If there would be a boxed game sold for this.  I would buy it without thinking twice, or even an Art Book of this.  I hope the developers make another game like this Monkey Island, Indiana Jones, Day of the Tentacle (Lucasarts / formerly Lucasfilms on the 1990s time) or the old Sierra on Line on its AGI games, (Those where their light years). A traditional point-and-click style adventure with a few logic puzzles and action-type mini games thrown in.  The plot is interesting, and the characters can be quite captivating despite the lack of any dialogue in the game (there are pop-up speech/thought bubbles with cutesy little animations in lieu of text, which works well).  Most of the puzzles were logical (a measure of this sort of game in my opinion is how many of the puzzles I think were stupid. In this case, very few if any).  There was a lot of pixel hunting, made harder by the touch interface. This was par for the course in the 90s, but I'm not sure that it's still the best way to go; I think that Broken Sword did a good job by highlighting all of the touchable things near where you'd just clicked, preventing your wondering if that thing you'd saw that would solve your puzzle were just a piece of the background or not.  The pencil sketch/water colour artwork is beautiful, and the music is excellent too. A mix of jazzy tunes, and mechanical clanking/electric buzzes and beeps that sounds odd but works really well in the style of the game.

The other complaint is that the game is way too short to be worth the 5 dollar price. I finished this game in about 5-6 hours. For 5 bucks I hope to get 10-15 hours out of a game.
